'''Rutherford Hayes Platt, Jr.''' (11 August 1894, Columbus, Ohio â 28 May 1975, Boston) was an American nature writer, photographer, and advertising executive.<ref name=Obit>{{cite newspaper|date=30 March 1975|page=37|newspaper=The New York Times|title=Rutherford Platt Dead at 80; Nature Writer, Photographer|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/03/30/archives/rutherford-platt-dead-at-80-nature-writer-photographer.html}}</ref>

==Biography==
Platt served in WW I as a lieutenant in Battery F, Three Hundred Twenty-Third Field Artillery and, with [[McDonald H. Riggs]], wrote a history of his unit.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Quarterly Journal of the New York State Historical Association|year=1921|pages=108â109|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K90TAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA108}}</ref> He received his bachelor's degree from Yale in 1918.<ref name=Obit/> In the early 1920s he was employed on the editorial staffs of ''[[The World's Work]]'' and of [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday Page & Company]]. He then became a corporate officer of Platt-Forbes, Inc., an advertising agency which represented several food and industrial companies, including [[Vought|Chance Vought Aircraft Corporation]]. In the midâ1950s he became president of Platt Productions Educational Films, specializing in nature films.<ref name=Obit/>

He attended classes at the [[Brooklyn Botanic Garden]] and by 1930 had become keenly interested in nature and, in particular, photography of plant life.<ref name=Obit/><ref>{{cite journal|title=The Language of Trees: On a Walk with Rutherford Platt|journal=American Forests|volume=124|issue=1|date=Spring 2018|author=Wojtech, Michael|url=https://www.questia.com/magazine/1G1-527473078/the-language-of-trees-on-a-walk-with-rutherford-platt}}</ref>

{{blockquote|Mr. Platt was botanist with Rear Adm. [[Donald B. MacMillan]]'s Arctic expeditions in 1947 and 1954. He was biology adviser to the Disney True Life Films in the early nineteenâfifties and was the author of âWalt Disney's Secrets of Life,â published in 1957.<ref name=Obit/>}}

Platt was elected a fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]]. He received the [[John Burroughs Medal]] in 1945 for his 1942 book ''This Green World''.<ref name=Obit/>

==Family==
Ratherford H. Platt, Jr.'s father was a son of a sister, Fanny Arabella ''nÃ©e'' Hayes,<ref>{{cite web|title=Platt, Rutherford Hayes|website=Rutherford B. Hayes Collections, rbhayes.org|url=https://www.rbhayes.org/collection-items/rutherford-b.-hayes-collections/platt-rutherford-hayes/}}</ref> of [[Rutherford B. Hayes]]. Rutherford H. Platt, Jr. died at age 80 and upon his death was survived by his widow, several children, nine grandchildren, and three great-grandchildren.<ref name=Obit/> At age 42, he divorced his first wife, Eleanor. In 1937 he married his second wife, Jean Dana ''nÃ©e'' Noyes.<ref>{{cite newspaper|date=2 May 1945|title=Niece Chief Legatee of A.D. Noyes' Estate|newspaper=NY Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1945/05/02/archives/niece-chief-legatee-of-ad-noyes-estate.html}} Jean Dana Noyes Platt was the niece of Alexander Dana Noyes, who was the financial editor of ''The New York Times'' for twenty-five years.</ref> There were two children from the first marriage and three children from the second marriage. One of his sons, Rutherford H. Platt, III, became a professor of geography at the University of Massachusetts Amherst<ref>{{cite newspaper|author=Platt, Rutherford H.|title=Gladden Social Justice Park an oasis of democracy|date=1 May 2018|newspaper=Daily Hampshire Gazette|url=http://www.gazettenet.com/Columnist-Rutherford-H-Platt-reflects-on-nation-s-first-social-justice-park-17180302}}</ref> and a specialist in land and water resource policy for urban areas.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rutherford H. Platt|website=UMassAmherst geosciences|url=https://www.geo.umass.edu/people/rutherford-h-platt}}</ref>

