{{Orphan|date=March 2018}}
'''Valer Clark Austin''' is a [[permaculture|permaculturalist]] involved with [[desert greening]]. Based in southern Arizona, she is known for promoting [[restoration ecology|ecological restoration]] through [[water conservation]] and [[holistic management (agriculture)|holistic land management]].<ref>[http://www.oprah.com/world/valer-austin-transforming-dead-land-in-mexico] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170130184548/http://www.oprah.com/world/Valer-Austin-Transforming-Dead-Land-in-Mexico |date=2017-01-30 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Dobie |first=Kathy |url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/09/21/living/oprah-rancher/index.html |title=An amateur rancher brings the wastelands of the Southwest back to life |website=CNN.com |date=2012-09-21 |accessdate=2017-04-25}}</ref>
Valer is a graduate of [[Hollins University]], from which she received the Hollins Distinguished Alumnae Award in June 2012.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollins.edu/175th-anniversary/distinguished-graduates/valer-clark-austin/|title=Valer Clark Austin - Hollins|work=Hollins|access-date=2018-02-26|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=":2" />
Valer later married to Josiah Austin, her current partner.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.oprah.com/world/valer-austin-transforming-dead-land-in-mexico|title=An Amateur Rancher Brings the Wastelands of the Southwest Back to Life|work=Oprah.com|access-date=2018-02-26|language=en-us}}</ref> The Austinâs have invested time and resources into the restoration of the watersheds in the Sonoran Desert region for the purposes of maintaining free open spaces and promotion of biodiversity.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://elinwa.org/awards/recipients/valer-and-josiah-austin|title=Valer and Josiah Austin {{!}} ELI National Wetlands Awards|website=elinwa.org|language=en|access-date=2018-02-26}}</ref> Their restoration efforts began with a 40-mile stretch which encompassed the El Coronado and Bar Boot Ranches.<ref name=":1" /> Acknowledging their important efforts, they began to grow their operation for the restoration of wetlands on a broader scale, such as, the borderland regions between the United States and Mexico.<ref name=":1" />
In the 1990s, the couple founded the Cuenca Los Ojos Foundation, which translates to "Watershed of the Springs",<ref name=":0" /> based at their El Coronado Ranch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cuencalosojos.org/pages/land-conservation|title=Land Conservation|website=Cuenca Los Ojos|access-date=2018-02-26}}</ref> The foundation encompassed various educators, scientists, ranchers in the area, and government agencies to restore and maintain the grasslands in the area, as well as, restore the habitats and biodiversity<ref name=":0" />
Notable Achievements include: * Protection of over 130,000 acres in Mexico<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://cuencalosojos.org/pages/support-us|title=Support Us|website=Cuenca Los Ojos|access-date=2018-02-26}}</ref> * Construction of 50 large gabions, 40,000 loose rock dams and 1000+ [[berm]]s in Mexico and the United States<ref name=":2" /> * Restoration of the Coues Deerâs and Gouldâs turkey in the Chiricahua Mountains, Arizona<ref name=":2" /> * Restoration of 5,000 acres of grasslands in Mexico with native vegetation<ref name=":2" /> Their work has been recognized by the [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fws.gov/southwest/fisheries/Eddies/Spring2010/article7/Eddies_spr2010_art7.pdf |format=PDF |title=Collaborative conservation on private lands |author=Jerewmy Voeltz |website=Fws.gov |accessdate=2017-04-25}}</ref> and the [[United States Geological Survey]],<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://geography.wr.usgs.gov/science/aridlands/Babocomari.html |title=Aridland Water Harvesting Study |doi=10.1111/j.1752-1688.1998.tb05961.x |website=Geography.wr.usgs.gov |date=2017-02-03 |accessdate=2017-04-25}}</ref> as well as [[The Nature Conservancy]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Tana Kappel |url=http://blog.nature.org/conservancy/2014/07/07/the-river-geronimo-knew/ |title=The River Geronimo Knew &#124; Conservancy Talk |website=Blog.nature.org |date=2014-07-07 |accessdate=2017-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.omlaw.com/azapp-blog/postings/2015/arizona-court-of-appeals-division-two-holds-that-a-signatory-to-an-agreement-that-includes-an-arbitration-provision-cannot-compel-arbitration/ |title=Arizona Court of Appeals Division Two holds that a signatory to an agreement that includes an arbitration provision cannot compel arbitration... < AZAPP Blog &#124; Osborn Maledon |website=Omlaw.com |date= |accessdate=2017-04-25}}</ref> In addition, Austin has served on the advisory board for the Borderlands Research Institute for Natural Resource Management at [[Sul Ross State University]], located in the [[Big Bend (Texas)|Big Bend]] region of [[West Texas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bri.sulross.edu/pubs/deserttracks/v7i3.pdf |format=PDF |title=Desert Tracks |date=2014 |volume=7 |website=Bri.sulross.edu |accessdate=2017-04-25}}</ref> In 2008, Valer and Josiah Austin were awarded the landowner stewardship award for their work at El Coronado Ranch.<ref name=":1" />
